# Django Deployment Guide (Ubuntu + Gunicorn + Nginx + systemd + SSL)

## Overview

This guide explains how to deploy a Django application on Ubuntu using:

* Gunicorn
* systemd
* Nginx
* Let's Encrypt SSL
* Cloudflare (optional)

The guide is designed for hosting **multiple Django projects** on the same server.

---

# Recommended Directory Structure

```
/home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/

├── Recruiter/
│   ├── manage.py
│   ├── recruiter/
│   ├── staticfiles/
│   ├── media/
│   └── venv/
│
├── CRM/
│   ├── manage.py
│   ├── crm/
│   ├── staticfiles/
│   ├── media/
│   └── venv/
│
└── API/
    ├── manage.py
    ├── api/
    ├── staticfiles/
    ├── media/
    └── venv/
```

Each project should have its own:

* Virtual environment
* Gunicorn service
* Nginx configuration

---

# 1. Install Required Packages

```
sudo apt update

sudo apt install python3-pip python3-venv nginx
```

Install Gunicorn inside your virtual environment:

```
pip install gunicorn
```

---

# 2. Configure Django

settings.py

```
ALLOWED_HOSTS = [
    "recruiter.example.com",
    "www.recruiter.example.com"
]
```

Collect static files

```
python manage.py collectstatic
```

---

# 3. Test Gunicorn

Before using systemd, verify Gunicorn works.

```
cd /home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter

source venv/bin/activate

gunicorn recruiter.wsgi:application --bind 127.0.0.1:8000
```

Open another terminal

```
curl http://127.0.0.1:8000
```

If this fails, do **not** continue.

Fix Django first.

---

# 4. Create systemd Service

```
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/recruiter.service
```

Example

```
[Unit]
Description=Recruiter Django Application
After=network.target

[Service]
User=ubuntu
Group=www-data

WorkingDirectory=/home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter

Environment="PATH=/home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter/venv/bin"

RuntimeDirectory=recruiter
RuntimeDirectoryMode=0755

ExecStart=/home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter/venv/bin/gunicorn \
    --workers 3 \
    --timeout 120 \
    --bind unix:/run/recruiter/gunicorn.sock \
    recruiter.wsgi:application

Restart=always
RestartSec=5

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Reload systemd

```
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
```

Enable

```
sudo systemctl enable recruiter
```

Start

```
sudo systemctl start recruiter
```

---

# 5. Verify systemd

```
sudo systemctl status recruiter
```

Expected

```
Active: active (running)
```

---

# 6. Verify Socket

```
find /run -name "*.sock"
```

Example

```
/run/recruiter/gunicorn.sock
```

Check permissions

```bash
ls -ld /run/recruiter/
ls -l /run/recruiter/
```

Check the socket directory ownership and fix it if needed:

```bash
ls -ld /run/recruiter
ls -l /run/recruiter/
```

If it shows only `root`, update the systemd service to use a runtime directory and restart Gunicorn:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/recruiter.service
```

Make sure this line is present under `[Service]`:

```ini
RuntimeDirectory=recruiter
```

Then reload systemd and restart the service:

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart recruiter
sudo systemctl status recruiter
```

If the socket still does not appear, check the logs:

```bash
sudo journalctl -u recruiter -n 100 --no-pager
```

Expected

```
srw-rw---- gunicorn.sock
```

---

# WARNING

If the socket does not exist

**DO NOT troubleshoot Nginx first.**

Gunicorn failed to start.

Check

```
sudo journalctl -u recruiter -n 100 --no-pager
```

---

# 7. Test Gunicorn Socket

```
curl --unix-socket /run/recruiter/gunicorn.sock http://localhost/
```

Expected

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
```

or

```
HTTP/1.1 302 Found
```

If

```
Failed to connect
```

Gunicorn is not running.

---

# 8. Configure Nginx

```
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/recruiter
```

HTTP

```
server {

    listen 80;

    server_name recruiter.example.com;

    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;

}
```

HTTPS

```
server {

    listen 443 ssl;
    http2 on;

    server_name recruiter.example.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;

    location / {

        include proxy_params;

        proxy_pass http://unix:/run/recruiter/gunicorn.sock;

    }

    location /static/ {

        alias /home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter/staticfiles/;

    }

    location /media/ {

        alias /home/ubuntu/Documents/projects/Recruiter/media/;

    }

}
```

Enable

```
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/recruiter /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
```

---

# 9. Test Nginx

```
sudo nginx -t
```

Expected

```
syntax is ok

test is successful
```

Reload

```
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

---

# 10. Verify Nginx

Ports

```
sudo ss -tlnp | grep nginx
```

Expected

```
0.0.0.0:80

0.0.0.0:443
```

---

Test locally

```
curl -H "Host: recruiter.example.com" http://127.0.0.1
```

---

Test HTTPS

```
curl -Ik https://127.0.0.1 -H "Host: recruiter.example.com"
```

---

# 11. Install Certbot

```
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx
```

Generate certificate

```
sudo certbot --nginx \
-d recruiter.example.com
```

For multiple subdomains

```
sudo certbot --nginx \
-d recruiter.example.com \
-d api.example.com \
-d crm.example.com
```

---

# 12. Cloudflare

Recommended SSL mode

```
Full (strict)
```

DNS

```
A recruiter -> EC2 Public IP
```

---

# 13. Firewall

UFW

```
sudo ufw allow OpenSSH

sudo ufw allow 80/tcp

sudo ufw allow 443/tcp

sudo ufw enable
```

AWS Security Group

Allow

* 22
* 80
* 443

